name: Trochodendron aralioides P.F.Siebold & J.G.Zuccarini
rightsHolder: Louisiana State University, Shirley C. Tucker Herbarium
locality: Grown in protected site in front of Museum Building, New York Botanical Garden, Bronx.; New York Botanical Garden
habitat: Plant accession number 415/57 (received from Carl English, Seattle, Washington, U.S.A., April 2, 1957). Shrub 3m tall, 15cm in diameter at the base, soon branching, the branches ascending-horizontal, in the manner of Cornus alternifolia L. f. Twigs somewhat brittle, with slight resinous exudate when dried over heat, ascending at tip, yellow-green until 6-8mm in diameter, then turning brown, the bark of lowermost stem beginning to furrow. Leaves evergreen, hence the species only marginally hardy here, brittle, coriaceous, neither they nor the twigs with any particular odor when crushed, dark green above, yellow-green below (as are the petioles), in arrangement and shape similar to some Araliaceae, e. g. Dendropanax arboreous (L.) Dcne. & Planch. Most twigs ending in erect inflorescences, the fruit green, its upper surface glaucous. Cultivated.
